@NODE 1 "Introduction... "
  @{B}What iz MenuBar v1.5?@{UB}

		MenuBar is a small (20K) CNet/3 PFile that can be uzed for
whatever you think it deserves a home.  I uze it in every @{B}sys.entry@{UB}
and a few other custom calls.  It's hard to describe exactly what it doez,
it's pretty self-explanatory when you run it in each of it's @{B}@{"five"
link 3}@{UB}
modez.  It basically iz an ANSI bar with three fields of text on it.  The
first field iz the name of yer BBS.  The second iz a random-quote that iz
read from a list that your uzers can add to.  The third field can be uzed
for a number of thingz.  You the SysOp fill that field with what ever you
want by sending MenuBar arguments when it's called. 

		MenuBar wuz first written in ARexx when it wuz still just
an idea, a small utility.  Then it's usage rate jumped, everyone wuz uzing
it, and became very slow.  I re-wrote a few routines for speed but knew
that my revisions were useless because ARexx iz just obviously slow.

		Anyhow, that's basically where it came from.  If you forget
the command template in the future, just run MenuBar from a Shell to get a
full template.
@ENDNODE 1

@NODE 2 "Installation... "
  @{B}How do I install it?@{UB}

		@{U}To install MenuBar@{UU}:

		o Copy the MenuBar program into whatever directory you wish
		  to run it from.  (I keep my copy in "PFiles:Utilz/")

		o Add these linez to your @{B}bbsmenu@{UB} file under the
		  @{B}2; Available everywhere@{UB} section:

		  	@{B}OLIST  |@{UB}[CTRL-Q]@{B}#2 @{UB}[Your Path]@{B}/MenuBar l}@{UB}
		  	@{B}OLINER |@{UB}[CTRL-Q]@{B}#2 @{UB}[Your Path]@{B}/MenuBar a}@{UB}
			@{B}CONFIG |@{UB}[CTRL-Q]@{B}#2 @{UB}[Your Path]@{B}/MenuBar c}@{UB}

		  If you want to use MenuBar's Prompt mode.  Edit line #68
		  in @{B}BBSTEXT@{UB} to:

		  [CTRL-Y]@{B}n2@{UB}[CTRL-Q]@{B}#2 @{UB}[Your Path]@{B}/MenuBar p}@{UB}

		  Feel free to change the command names from @{B}OLIST@{UB} and
		  @{B}OLINER@{UB} to whatever you think iz appropriate.

		o Re-load yer BBSMENU/BBSTEXTs from the CNet/3 Control
		  Panel and type CONFIG from CNet/3.  (Or whatever you
		  chose az the @{B}Config@{UB} mode command name)

		o MenuBar will clear the screen and bring up the config
		  panel.  From here, you can change the name of your BBS to
		  change the colours of just about everything.  It's a very
		  easy-to-use interface, i'm sure you'll figure out.
			
		  After your satisfied with your personal customization,
		  hit 'Q' for quit and answer 'Y'up! to the 'Save?'
		  requester.  MenuBar will then create two files in the
		  path from which he was called.

		  NOTE:  Do NOT attempt to edit these two filez with a Text
		         editor!  If you must edit sumthing that you can
	 	 	 not change from within MenuBar's Config panel,
			 then use a bit editor like @{B}ArtSoft
		         Development's Zaphod@{UB}.

		That's it.  Now MenuBar haz been installed and iz ready for
		a hopefully long and prosperous life.
@ENDNODE 2

@NODE 3 "How it werx... "
  @{B}How doez MenuBar werk?@{UB}

		MenuBar haz four modez.  @{B}Add@{UB}, @{B}Display@{UB},
		@{B}List@{UB}, and @{B}Config@{UB}.

		@{U}Add@{UU}
		To invoke MenuBar in @{B}Add@{UB} mode, the first argument that
		MenuBar must be called with iz "@{B}a@{UB}".  For example:

			MenuBar a

		You will be prompted to enter a One Liner (Quote) on the
		menu bar.  Enter "@{B}N@{UB}" or just hit [ENTER] to abort if
		you wish not to save yer One Liner.

		@{U}Display@{UU}
		To invoke MenuBar in @{B}Display@{UB} mode, the first
		argument that MenuBar must be called with iz "@{B}d@{UB}".
		The left-over arguments will be added to the third
		<location/comment> field.  MenuBar will only display the
		first @{B}19@{UB} characterz of the left-over argument.  For
		example:

			MenuBar d Message Base

		MenuBar will show himself with a random quote in the middle
		at once in this mode.

		@{U}List@{UU}
		To reveal MenuBar's @{B}List@{UB} mode, the first argument
		that MenuBar must recieve from the command line iz "@{B}l@{UB}".
		
		MenuBar will clear the screen and display the quotes in a
		Page-by-Page mode along with each quote's author to the
		right of the quote itself.  To exit from this mode, hit @{B}Q@{UB}!
		
		NOTE:  MenuBar will expand and show more per screen depending
		       on the height of yer terminal.

	MenuBar readz and writes to the Quote file in a random-access
	binary mode.  This ensures that the size of the Quote file won't slow
	down the display of the MenuBar in @{B}Display@{UB} mode.
@ENDNODE 3

